(this.webpackJsonpdemo=this.webpackJsonpdemo||[]).push([[10],{271:function(e,t,a){e.exports={header:"Course_header__18DMp",paragraph:"Course_paragraph__1HKzN",border:"Course_border__2W79w",gridContainer:"Course_gridContainer__15V_a"}},301:function(e,t,a){"use strict";a.r(t),a.d(t,"default",(function(){return h}));var n=a(259),s=a(244),r=a(271),o=a.n(r),i=a(1);function h(){return Object(i.jsxs)(n.a,{children:[Object(i.jsx)("h1",{className:o.a.header,children:"Bonds & Bond Yield"}),Object(i.jsx)(s.a,{className:o.a.line}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Bonds are different from stocks. Bonds are relatively safer and less risky. They can be used as an asset for an investor to provide semi -yearly or yearly or quarterly cash flow (depend on the bonds)."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Bond is simply a loan taken out by a company. Instead of going to a bank, the company gets the money from investors who buy its bonds. In exchange for the capital, the company pays an interest coupon\u2014the annual interest rate paid on a bond."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Bonds are financial instruments which are relatively a Safe bet for an investor to invest in. Bonds are issued by an company , Non-Banking finance institutions , Banking institutions and also government institutions."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Here is the logic, let\u2019s assume that government wants to raise funds to develop a hospital in a town. The government needs funds for that hospital,, but the government does not have the funds for creating a hospital. So what government can do is they can issue bonds, which can be bought by investors. The government sell the bonds at a price say 1 bond for 10 rupees. The government issue as many bonds as they want , to fulfil the need of the money requirement. Now here is how the bonds works."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Bonds have a maturity date. What that means is bonds have a fixed tenure and with fixed interest rates and after those tenure ends, you will get your principal amount back along with interest. Maturity date is the date when the principal or par amount of the bond is paid to investors and the company\u2019s or issuer of bond obligation ends."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"As the promoter here is government, the risk involved in these investments is negligible. You are guaranteed to get your money back, that too with interest rates. But these interest rates are not as high as compare to money you can earn by investing in stock market value investing. So many argue that while bonds are safe, they don\u2019t provide much returns to investors. While some Investors use bonds to maintain liquidity( cash in hand) and whenever they see an investment opportunity in different investment avenues, they use these bonds to invest in that. Bonds are a good financial instruments to have liquidity."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"When you invest in Bonds, you will get your money back at an interest rate. This interest rate is set when you invest in bonds. The bonds are purchased by investors who are interested in earning a fixed interest in a fixed tenure. After you have purchased the bonds , its interest rate cannot change and its tenure cannot change. Changing interest rates of bonds by the promoters changes its price structure. Let\u2019s see how that happens."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Bonds have an inverse relationship to interest rates. For example imagine you buy a bond for 10 rupees at 2 % interest rate for a period of 2 years. After 6 months, the promoters issue new bonds which give interest rate of 4 % on the bonds that you were holding. If you have to sell your bonds in the open market, then you have to lower your price. That\u2019s because why would anyone want to buy a 2% interest rate bond over 4 % interest rate bonds. If you plan to hold the bond until the end of the its time period , then selling bonds is really not your concern and you don\u2019t need to take much concern in it."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"A bond can be secured or unsecured. A secured bond pledges specific assets to bondholders if the company cannot repay the obligation. This asset is also called collateral on the loan. So if the bond issuer defaults, the asset is then transferred to the investor.."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Unsecured bonds, on the other hand, are not backed by any collateral. That means the interest and principal are only guaranteed by the issuing company. Also called debentures, these bonds return little of your investment if the company fails. \ufeff As such, they are much riskier than secured bonds."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"If the issue of bonds is not by the government but by a company , first check out that company financial health before investing in their bonds. When buying bonds , there is a risk of issuer defaulting on their commitment due to various reasons like they ran out of funds, the company is performing poorly and cannot repay its debt, etc. When you buy bonds , you take on this risk of default. So if you are buying bonds from Non-government sources, keep a eye on how is the issuer doing and what financial health is issuer in."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Some government bonds may provide you opportunity to earn money tax \u2013free. You can keep a lookout on such bonds as not only these bonds safe, but also by being tax free, it increases your rate of returns from the investment."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"There is another risk associated with bonds. It is called prepayment risk. Prepayment risk is the risk that a given bond issue will be paid off earlier than expected, normally through a call provision. With a call provision added to the bond, the corporation can pay the debt off early. When buying bonds see if this call provision is there or not."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Consider a bond that is issued by a company or government for Rs. 100 with a coupon of 7% for a period of five years. This implies that every year , the issuer will pay interest of 7% while the principal will be refunded after the bond matures. What drives the bond market is the fact that bondholders are free to sell their bonds before maturity."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"The face value of a bond is what it sold for initially. Since they are transferable through sales in the bond market , their value fluctuates . The returns accured by holders is measured by the yield, which is the rate of interest paid as coupons."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Yield is calculated as the coupon divided by the value of the bond. It is multiplied by 100 to be expressed in percentage. In effect, yield = (coupon/value) *100"}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Yield= CouponValue \xd7 100"}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"In the example above, if the face value of the bond fell to Rs.80, the yield would rise to 8.75%, that is (7/80*100). Correspondilgy , if the value rose to Rs. 120 , the yield would drop to 5.83%, that is (7/120*100)."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"It should be noted that even if the value of a bond fluctuates , the amount that can be redeemed after the term of maturity is reached is the face value, which is Rs.100 in this case. Bond yield is inversely proportional to its current value. The greater the yield, the lower the current market price of the bond."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Conventional metrics used by economist to diagnose the health of a country economy include inflation, repo rate of central banks, growth rate and national income . However , bond yields are also the means of analysing economy in a indirect way. As investors sell Government bonds, price drop, ad yield increases. A higher yield indicates greater risk. If the yield offered by a bond is much higher than what it was when issued, there is a chance that the company or government that issued it is financially stressed and may not be able to repay the capital ."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Government bonds are relatively more stable, but low demand at auctions indicate low investor confidence in the country economy."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("p",{className:o.a.paragraph,children:"Now we move on to the next investment avenue , mutual funds."}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{}),Object(i.jsx)("br",{})]})}}}]);
